							<h4 class="mb-4">Regulations on cryptocurrencies in Vietnam</h4>
							<p>In Vietnam, there are currently no legal documents defining the concept of cryptocurrencies. However, a number of documents stipulating the forms of electronic money include e-wallets, prepaid cards ... such as the Law on the State Bank (2010), the Law on Credit Institutions (2010), Decree No. 101/2012 / ND-CP of the Government on non-cash payments and Decree No. 80/2016 / ND-CP amending and supplementing a number of articles of Decree No. 101/2012 / ND-CP, Circular No. 19/2016 / TT-NHNN regulates bank card operations (amended by Circular No. 26/2017 / TT-NHNN). Currently, the Draft Decree stipulating the amended non-cash payment has agreed to provide a clear definition of cryptocurrencies: “Cryptocurrency is the value of currency stored on electronic media. prepayment by customers to banks, foreign bank branches, intermediary payment service providers to perform payment transactions and to ensure the corresponding value at the bank, including: payment card before, electronic wallet, mobile money ".</p>
							<p>In summary, the regulations on cryptocurrencies in the draft are quite comprehensive, consistent with international practices and practices in Vietnam, covering the most important characteristics of cryptocurrencies and ensuring ability to clearly distinguish between cryptocurrencies and cryptocurrencies, as well as protect the interests of customers. The decree on non-cash payments replaces Decree No. 101/2012 / ND-CP dated November 22, 2012 with clear definitions and regulations on “cryptocurrencies” expected to help eliminate confusion, making the operation of the market and management easier, thereby promoting non-cash payment in Vietnam.</p>
